	  <title>Orthogonal Projection of a Vector on a Line: Exercises</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <caption>Concept comprehension</caption>
         <problem.body>
			
			         <para>
               <para.body>In regards to the projection of a vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> along a nonzero vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math>, which of the following are true?</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>This projection is a number in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>No! If <math>
                              <latex> n &gt; 1 </latex>
                           </math>, the projection is a vector. – If <math>
                              <latex>n=1</latex>
                           </math>, the projection vector may also be interpreted as a number.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>				
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>This projection is a vector.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Yes! The projection vector is a multiple of the vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>		
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>This projection is a line.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>No! We start with a vector, and projecting it onto a line <math>
                              <latex>L</latex>
                           </math> yields a single vector contained in <math>
                              <latex>L</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>		
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>, what can you conclude about <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in relation to the line  <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math>?</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <answer.exercise>
            <answer.exercise.block>
               <answer.exercise.block.body>
				              <para>
                     <para.body>We can conclude that <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
			            </answer.exercise.block.body>
            </answer.exercise.block>
         </answer.exercise>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>, we claim that <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math>. To see this, recall</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>\pr_{L(\Vect{x})} = \dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{\Vect{y} } } \cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Given that <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y} \neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>, the expression on the right hand side vanishes exactly when</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>\dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{ \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} } } = 0</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Now this ratio takes the value <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> if and only if its numerator is <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>; i.e. <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                     </math>, and this happens exactly when <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
