				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>of <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x} = (-1,1)</latex>
                     </math> onto the line <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> consisting of all those points <math>
                        <latex>(x,y)</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> satisfying <math>
                        <latex>x=-t</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>y = 3t</latex>
                     </math>, where <math>
                        <latex>t</latex>
                     </math> is in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x} = (2/5) \cdot (-1,3)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We know that a point on <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> is of the form <math>
                           <latex>(x,y) = (-t,3t) = t\cdot (-1,3)</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> has the direction of <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y} = (-1,3)</latex>
                        </math>. So the require projection is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\pr_{\Vect{y}}(\Vect{x}) = \dfrac{ (-1,1) \bullet (-1,3) }{ \DotPr{ (-1,3) }{ (-1,3) } } \cdot (-1,3) = \dfrac{2}{5} \cdot (-1,3)</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>of <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x} = (2,3)</latex>
                     </math> onto the line of all those <math>
                        <latex>(x,y)</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> satisfying <math>
                        <latex>2x - y = 0</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x}) = (8/5)\cdot (1,2)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>First find a nonzero vector in the direction of the given line. – There are infinitely many such vectors. Any one will do.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>A vector has the direction of the given line if it is perpendicular to any of the normal vectors to the line.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>A nonzero vector in the direction of <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> is <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a} = (1,2)</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore the required projection vector is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\pr_{\Vect{a}}(\Vect{x}) = \dfrac{ \DotPr{ (2,3) }{ (1,2) } }{ \DotPr{ (1,2) }{ (1,2) } } \cdot (1,2) = \dfrac{8}{5} \cdot (1,2)</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
